</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles City Councilman Michael Woo urged a city agency Friday to seize a 
developer's $250,000 bond because the developer failed to install traffic 
improvements to ease congestion in Studio City. 
</P>
<P>
The Board of Public Works took no action on Woo's request. 
</P>
<P>
The target of Woo's anger is the developer of the 25,000-square-foot Times 
Square mall at 12215 Ventura Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
Diana Brueggemann, a deputy of Woo, said the development team, led by Mitch 
Francis, was required to post a $250,000 bond with the city to guarantee that 
he would install a double left-turn lane at Ventura and Laurel Canyon 
boulevards and other improvements. But the work has not been done, she said. 
</P>
<P>
Steve Getzoff, a partner in the Times Square project, complained that the 
development group has spent $50,000 on traffic studies but has been unable to 
get the city to decide what improvements are needed. 
</P>
