<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMP CARE SELLING IRVINE BUILDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Staff Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Comprehensive Care Corp., the troubled owner of a chain of drug and alcohol 
treatment centers, said Friday it had agreed to sell its former corporate 
headquarters in Irvine for $9 million to an unidentified buyer. 
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive Care said last year it would move to Missouri and sell most of 
its assets in California in order to pay a pressing $25-million debt. 
</P>
<P>
That announcement came shortly after a deal to merge with a Virginia hospital 
company fell through in October when the hospital's lender backed out. 
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive Care said in a statement that the sale of its two-story building 
at 18551 Von Karman Avenue depends on the results of a test for environmental 
contamination demanded by the buyer, a test not yet complete. The buyer has put 
down a $500,000 deposit, but the company says the sale also depends on the 
buyer raising the rest of the purchase price. 
</P>
<P>
Comprehensive Care operates the CareUnit Hospitals for drug and alcohol 
treatment, among other businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
COMPREHENSIVE CARE CORP; DIVESTMENT; PROPERTY SALES 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
